<DOC><DOCNO> ZF32-141-116 </DOCNO><DOCID>11 024 697</DOCID><JOURNAL>Journal of Systems Management  June 1991 v42 n6 p28(3).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>The feasibility of converting to an open systems architecture.andO;(case study of Newton Manufacturing Corp.)andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Schneider, Dan.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Newton, IA based Newton Manufacturing Co, a $48 millionpromotional goods distributor, found that its rising sales andnumber of customers was burdening its lone mainframe computer.andO;Newton's MIS department, outside consultants and NCR Corp workedtogether to assess the company's data processing needs.andP;  The studyconcentrated on the possibility of migrating from a hierarchical,mainframe-oriented system to an open, client/server database.andP;  Thetask was huge, in large part because of the many functionssupported by Newton's computer system, including accounts payable,accounts receivable, order entry and shipping.andP;  It was determinedthat the mainframe system could not support a rise in customerdemand, whereas an open system could.andP;  Another problem was posedby the sheer number of products that Newton carries and thecomplexity of its ordering process.andP;  A Newton group is currentlyinterviewing workers at each department in an effort to define thenew computer environment.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Company:   Newton Manufacturing Co. (Data processing).andO;Topic:     Open SystemsClient/Server ArchitectureCase StudySystem ConversionRequirements AnalysisDistributors.andO;Feature:   illustrationtable.andO;Caption:   A list of Newton's deliverables and benefits. (table)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>